making independent and studio films: Penny Allen, Karen Arthur, Anne Bancroft, Joan Darling, Lee Grant, Barbara Loden, Elaine May, Barbara Peeters, Joan Rivers, Stephanie Rothman, Beverly Sebastian, Joan Micklin Silver, Joan Tewkesbury, Jane Wagner, Nancy Walker, and Claudia Weill. Drawing on interviews conducted by the author, Liberating Hollywood is the first study of women directors within the intersection of second wave feminism, civil rights legislation, and Hollywood to investigate the remarkable careers of these filmmakers during one of the most mythologized periods in American film history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFeminism and motion pictures. 0aFeminist filmszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aWomen in the motion picture industryzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen motion picture producers and directorszUnited States. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh  awomen, filmmakers, social justice, sexism, racism, film, United States, Hollywood, Penny Allen, Karen Arthur, Anne Bancroft, Joan Darling, Lee Grant, Barbara Loden, Elaine May, Barbara Peeters, Joan Rivers, Stephanie Rothman, Beverly Sebastian, Joan Micklin Silver, Joan Tewkesbury, Jane Wagner, Nancy Walker, Claudia Weill, directors, feminism, feminist, second wave feminism, civil rights, American.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311066608308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065352640uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081358750940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813587509423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813587509.jpg  a978-3-11-065352-6  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  a978-3-11-066608-3  Rutgers University Press Complete e